<h3>2. Pivotal Phase III: CTR-1011 (Falutz et al., 2010 — JAIDS)</h3>

<p>The second pivotal study enrolled <strong>404 patients</strong> with a similar design and confirmed the findings: visceral fat decreased by approximately 18% in the tesamorelin group compared to a 1% reduction in the placebo group (P &lt; 0.001). The concordance between both trials was a key factor in the FDA's approval decision. Importantly, this study included a 12-month extension phase that showed effects were maintained with continued treatment — and reversed when tesamorelin was stopped, confirming the drug's causal role.</p>

<h3>3. NAFLD / Liver Fat (Stanley et al., 2019 — The Lancet HIV)</h3>

<p>This is where tesamorelin's story gets even more exciting. A randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial at Massachusetts General Hospital and the NIH enrolled <strong>61 people with HIV and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</strong> (NAFLD) — a condition affecting 30-40% of the HIV-positive population and an increasingly common metabolic problem in the general population.</p>

